steps.body:
Hi {{first_name}},

I run a small creative studio in Bristol — Studio IOS — built specifically around apparel direction, graphic language and trend intelligence for sports and entertainment licensing programmes. We're embedded inside the combat-sports apparel space (FUJI Sports, Phalanx) and the work that comes out of those engagements has been used to set retail-grade graphic standards across multiple licensee categories.

{{custom_hook}}

I've put together a short read on where retail-grade graphic language is heading inside {{company}}'s category over the next 18 months — drawn from what we're seeing across the licensees we work with. Happy to send it over if you'd find it useful. No agenda, no follow-up sales process.

{{signature}}

Hi {{first_name}},

I'll keep this brief. Two months in, and I've not pushed for a conversation because I don't think Tier-1 licensing relationships start that way.

But if any of the trend direction, style-guide architecture, or apparel-programme work I've sent over has resonated, I'd value 30 minutes of your time to introduce Studio IOS properly and understand what {{company}}'s creative roadmap looks like over the next two seasons.

{{signal_phrase}}

If now isn't the moment, I'll respect that and keep my touches sector-relevant rather than promotional.

{{signature}}

{{first_name}},

Studio IOS — Bristol-based creative direction studio. We sit inside the combat-sports and action-sports world: FUJI, Phalanx, and a stack of brands you'd recognise.

{{custom_hook}}

Reason for the note: founders in the £1M–£10M range often get caught between manufacturer capacity and trend intelligence. Manufacturers can produce; they can't art-direct. The result is collections that ship on time but feel reactive instead of anticipatory.

{{tier_proof}}

Worth a 20-minute call before {{company}}'s next collection window?

{{signature}}
